\begin_inset Formula $B=CA$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $C\in\mathbb{R}^{k\times m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Assume without loss of generality that and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=0\Rightarrow Bx=0$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{null}\left(A\right)\subset\text{null}\left(B\right)$
\end_inset

.
 By the fundamental theorem of Linear Algebra and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{row}\left(A\right)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{row}\left(B\right)\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{null}\left(A\right)\cup\text{row}\left(A\right)=\text{null}\left(B\right)\cup\text{row}\left(B\right)=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{null}\left(A\right) & \subset\text{null}\left(B\right)\\
 & \iff\\
\overline{\text{null}\left(A\right)} & \subset\overline{\text{null}\left(B\right)}\\
 & \iff\\
\text{row}\left(B\right) & \subset\text{row}\left(A\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,k$
\end_inset

 there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{T}c_{i}=b_{i}^{T}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}^{T}=\left(B^{T}\right)_{i}$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th row of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Collecting all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 into a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{T}$
\end_inset

 we get that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{T}C^{T}=B^{T}
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CA=B
\]

\end_inset


